<br>
So a few months ago, I decided to see if I could get my Brell-worshipping Dwarf Paladin to gain enough Cabilis faction standing to be able to bank there.  So as not to keep you in suspense as to the outcome:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.firstnethou.com/dcd/cabilis/bank.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
The story of how I did it follows.<br>
<br>
There are six faction groups in Cabilis:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE CODE START--><pre> 
LegionOfCabilis:       Warrior guild (including Troopers and Warlords)
CrusadersOfGreenmist:  Shadowknight guild (including most Crusaders)
ScaledMystics:         Shaman guild
BroodOfKotiz:          Necromancer guild
Swifttails:            Monk guild
CabilisResidents:      Bankers, most vendors, miscellaneous NPCs
</pre><!--EZCODE CODE END--><br>
The faction group necessary for banking/vending privileges is the CabilisResidents faction.  However, the catch is that all the ways to increase CabilisResidents faction standing require dealing with the Iksars who are on the LegionOfCabilis faction.  So they're the first that you'll need to work on.<br>
<br>
To increase your faction standing with LegionOfCabilis, kill Sarnaks and/or Goblins and/or &quot;outcast&quot; Iksar (bandits, footpads, pariahs, etc.) around Kunark.  Lots and lots and lots (did I mention lots?) of them.<br>
<br>
I had to kill 1,314 Sarnak+Iksar+Goblins (mostly Goblins) before the Troopers finally /conned &quot;Glaring&quot; to me, and a total of 1,562 before I was finally &quot;Dubious&quot; (and thus non-KoS) to the Troopers.  This sounds like a lot (and it is), but it took me only about a week of dedicated &quot;kill it if it gives faction&quot; to reach that point.  And anyone who has made a career of leveling in Kunark (I hadn't) may already have killed that many.<br>
<br>
There is every indication that the level of the Goblin/Sarnak/Iksar makes no difference to the amount of faction gain (all give 1 point of increase).  So the newbie goblin hills to the west of the Cabilis entrance in Warslik's Woods is a good place to commit mass Goblin genocide.  If you're of sufficient level, the Goblin fort in northern WW is great too, I got a lot of faction increases while clearing and reclearing the Fort hoping to get a Totem of the Warrior Spirit from Grachnist the Destroyer (and I succeeded).<br>
<br>
At this point, it was time to move to Field of Bone.  At the Cabilis gate in FoB, you'll find Trooper Mozo.  For four Bone Chips, he'll give you one point of faction increase with five different groups:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE CODE START--><pre> 
   Your faction standing with LegionOfCabilis got better.
   Your faction standing with CabilisResidents got better.
   Your faction standing with ScaledMystics got better.
   Your faction standing with CrusadersOfGreenmist got better.
   Your faction standing with Swifttails got better.
   You gain experience!!
   You receive 2 silver from Trooper Mozo.
</pre><!--EZCODE CODE END--><br>
This covers every faction group in Cabilis EXCEPT the Necromancers, and you don't really need them for anything.<br>
<br>
From here on out there are only two impediments to increasing Cabilis faction.<br>
<br>
The first problem is reaching Trooper Mozo without getting creamed by the roaming Crusaders, who you will still be very KoS to.  There are two of them in the FoB around the Cabilis entrance:  Crusader Bodli, and Crusader Quarg.  Interestingly, although almost every Crusader in and around Cabilis are on the SK faction group (CrusadersOfGreenmist), including Bodli, for some reason Crusader Quarg happens to be on the Shaman faction group (ScaledMystics).  In order to avoid getting stomped by the Crusaders, I very strongly recommend starting an Iksar newbie as a &quot;spy&quot;, and using it to follow the two Crusaders around until you become familiar with the pattern of their rounds.  This makes it MUCH easier to avoid their patrols.  Here's a map of the FoB are around Cabilis:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.firstnethou.com/dcd/cabilis/fob.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
The red line shows the path you should take sneaking up to the gate -- stay high on the hills surrounding the city &quot;pavement&quot; until you make your last dash up to the gate.  The yellow line shows Crusader Bodli's patrol path.  Note that as he comes out of the city gate, he makes a left, walking right along the path you need to follow to approach the gate, so look sharp and don't run into him head-on.  The blue line shows Crusader Quarg's patrol path,  you shouldn't run into him if you follow the red line into, and then back out of, the city area.  Note:  Once you reach Trooper Mozo, if you stand close as possible to the &quot;torch&quot; without being out of &quot;Trade&quot; range with Trooper Mozo, you will be (barely) far enough from the Crusaders as they march into and out of the city gate to avoid aggro.  But it takes nerves of steel to stand there as they walk that close by you.<br>
<br>
The second impediment to good Cabilis faction is having the dedication required to gather the MASSIVE number of Bone Chips necessary to bring your remaining Cabilis faction standings up to a usable level (Apprehensive or better to the bankers/merchants, and non-KoS to most everyone else).  To reach the point where I could bank, I had to turn in 7,596 Bone Chips (1,899 quest completions).  That is not a typo.<br>
<br>
The good news is that the best source of Bone Chips in all of Norrath is right there in Field of Bone:  Kurn's Tower.  It's full of skeletons in the 10-18 range, and they almost always drop Bone Chips (up to 3 at once some times).  Even the Burynai in the basement often drop Bone Chips.  Plus, there are a lot of lowbie Iksars hunting there, and they are frequently glad to sell the stacks of bone chips that they have acquired.<br>
<br>
I lived in Kurn's Tower for a full week and a half before I had gathered enough Bone Chips to be able to walk the streets of Cabilis.  Here are some highlights from my visit:<br>
<br>
